[49m[38;5;9m- 393     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **The conversation log is PHI by association even when no clinical content is exchanged.** A patient interacting with the institution's FAQ bot has identified themselves as a patient of the institution. The conversation log is a HIPAA-relevant record. Audit logging, encryption, access controls, and retention policies apply. The architecture treats this as the floor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The conversation log is PHI by association even when no clinical content is exchanged.** A patient interacting with the institution's FAQ bot has identified themselves as a patient of the institution. The conversation log is a HIPAA-relevant record. Audit logging, encryption, access controls, and retention policies apply. The architecture treats this as the floor, not the ceiling. Session-token discipline (per-channel TTL, session isolation, no cross-channel bridging without explicit patient action) prevents inadvertent session leakage. The shared-device problem gets an explicit "clear conversation" patient affordance and aggressive session expiry for unauthenticated channels. Patients will volunteer PHI even in FAQ contexts ("I take metformin, when does your pharmacy close?"), so the architecture includes an inadvertent-PHI redaction layer with a taxonomy of sensitive categories (conditions, medications, account numbers, dates of birth, addresses, SSNs, payer IDs, family names) with per-category redact-or-redirect policy. Patient-rights workflows (access requests for conversation history, deletion requests that propagate as deletion-markers within regulatory-retention windows) integrate with the institution's existing rights-handling infrastructure. The conversation-log-for-analytics boundary is separate from the conversation-log-for-audit boundary, with de-identification before the analytics layer ingests content. The privacy officer plus patient-experience team are canonical owners of this governance surface.
